ent prevents posterior displacement of the tibia","The medial collateral ligament resists varus forces","The lateral collateral ligament resists valgus forces"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe knee joint relies on four main ligaments for stability, each with specific functions in preventing abnormal movement. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cruciate ligament prevents posterior displacement of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E by acting as a restraint against posterior translation of the tibia on the femur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe lateral collateral ligament is more often damaged than the medial collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - MCL injuries occur more frequently than LCL injuries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe anterior cruciate ligament prevents posterior displacement of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - The ACL actually prevents forward (anterior) movement of the tibia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe medial collateral ligament resists varus forces\u003C/strong\u003E - The MCL resists valgus forces, not varus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe lateral collateral ligament resists valgus forces\u003C/strong\u003E - The LCL resists varus forces, not valgus forces\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medial collateral ligament (MCL) resists valgus forces applied to the knee, whilst the lateral collateral ligament (LCL) resists varus forces","The posterior cruciate ligament (PCL) prevents posterior displacement of the tibia relative to the femur.","The anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) prevents anterior displacement of the tibia relative to the femur."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18277"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:14:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:17:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10991"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81715"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"